What is Consistency?
When you have multiple servers/databases, consistency defines:
“Will all users see the same data at the same time?”

1. Strong Consistency
Idea:
After a write → every read immediately sees latest data
Example:
	• You update your bank balance → refresh → always latest 
	• No stale data ever 
Real-world:
	• Banking systems 
	• Payment systems 
	• Inventory (last item left) 
How it works:
	• Writes are synchronous 
	• All replicas updated before response 
Trade-off:
	• Slower 
	• Less scalable 

 “Strong consistency means no confusion—everyone sees the same truth instantly.”

2. Eventual Consistency
Idea:
After a write → system eventually becomes consistent
Example:
	• Update profile picture → some users still see old one for few seconds 
	• DNS updates take time 
Real-world:
	• Social media feeds 
	• DNS systems 
	• Caching layers 
How it works:
	• Writes are asynchronous 
	• Replicas updated gradually 
Trade-off:
	• Fast 
	• Highly scalable 
	•  Temporary stale data 

 “Eventual consistency means it may be wrong now, but it will be right soon.”

 3. Causal Consistency
Idea:
Related operations stay in order, unrelated can be out of order
Example:
	• You post → then comment
Everyone must see post before comment
But other users’ posts can appear in any order 
Real-world:
	• Social media timelines 
	• Chat applications 
How it works:
	• Maintains “happens-before” relationship 
	• Tracks dependencies 
Trade-off:
	• Balanced approach 
	• More complex than eventual 
One-liner:
 “Causal consistency keeps cause and effect in order.”

Quick Comparison
Type	Speed	Accuracy	Use Case
Strong	Slow	⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐	Banking
Eventual	Fast	⭐⭐	Social media
Causal	Medium	⭐⭐⭐⭐	Chat / feeds
